citeinfo.title: 100-Meter Resolution Color Shaded Relief of Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands

pubinfo.publish: National Atlas of the United States

descript.abstract: The Color Shaded Relief of Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands map layer is a 100-meter resolution color-sliced elevation image of Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands, with relief shading added to accentuate terrain features, in an Albers Equal-Area Conic projection. The image was produced by combining the 100-meter resolution color-sliced elevation and the grayscale shaded relief data sets that are distributed by the National Atlas of the United States. The color shaded relief data were derived from the National Atlas 100-meter resolution elevation data. The elevation data were derived from National Elevation Dataset (NED) data and show the terrain of the conterminous United States at a resolution of 100 meters. The NED is a raster product assembled by the U.S. Geological Survey, designed to provide national elevation data in a seamless form with a consistent datum, elevation unit, and projection. Data corrections made in the NED assembly process minimize artifacts, permit edge matching, and fill sliver areas of missing data. More information on NED can be found at .
descript.purpose: The 100-meter resolution color shaded relief data were developed to portray the terrain of the United States at 1:1,000,000 scale. They are intended primarily for visual purposes. The original NED data should be used for conducting analysis and determining the most accurate elevation values. No responsibility is assumed by the National Atlas of the United States in the use of these data.

procstep.procdesc:
The color shaded relief image is a combination of the color-sliced elevation map layer and the grayscale shaded relief map layer that are distributed by the National Atlas of the United States. Characteristics and development of those two data sets are documented in their respective metadata. The two source files were combined in Photoshop in the following steps:
In Photoshop, National Atlas PR Color Sliced Elevation 2013 was opened as an Index color image and colors loaded from a Photoshop color look-up table. The metadata for National Atlas PR Color Sliced Elevation 2013 contains a listing of classes and color values. The Photoshop color look-up table file is available on request.
Color separation settings were set to UCR, No black generation, 300 percent maximum CMY.
The color-sliced elevation image was converted from Index mode to CMYK mode. The color separation settings ensured that all colors were CMY only.
National Atlas PR Grayscale Shaded Relief 2013 was copied and pasted into the K band of the new image.
Color separation settings were re-set to UCR, Maximum black generation, 400 percent maximum CMYK.
The new CMYK image was converted to RGB to create the final image.
Ocean areas were set to an RGB value of (193,224,250). Non-U.S. areas (if any) were set to an RGB value of (240,235,211).
